01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:18.000
I wonder what they would think to the following considerations,

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:25.000
that the person who said to say of what is that it is is true,

01:06:25.000 --> 01:06:28.000
to say of what it is that it is is true,

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:33.000
to say of what is that it is not is false, and then the other two variations,

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:39.000
has given in that a quite precise and clear account of truth for natural languages.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:46.000
And what Tarski did was to do something to give an account of truth for languages,

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:52.000
unlike natural languages which were capable of variable interpretations.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:59.000
So the Tarski definition is an account of how you take a semantics

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:07.000
and then give the truth conditions under a whole class of different interpretations of that particular syntax.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:11.000
And that doesn't seem to me to add anything to the notion of truth,

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:14.000
as far as it's concerned with natural language.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:20.000
I'd like to know your opinion.

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:34.000
The dissertation matter, Tarski certainly wouldn't feel particularly creative about that.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:42.000
I think the value of that is just that he brings out emphatically in the open, the sort

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:51.480
of thing that does cover the whole ground, but where his prowess comes in is in setting

01:07:51.480 --> 01:08:03.600
up a recursive definition that covers the ground in a finite space, whereas if we left

01:08:03.600 --> 01:08:16.680
it at the level of this quotation, there's infinitely many sentences that could be disquoted,

01:08:16.680 --> 01:08:21.760
and so a finite definition wouldn't be forthcoming.

01:08:21.760 --> 01:08:30.600
I see Tarski's definition of truth as having the virtue of putting the truth, putting the

01:08:30.600 --> 01:08:46.720
predicate into explicit, finite and eliminable form, and of course, incidentally, because

01:08:46.720 --> 01:08:55.920
of the paradoxes, Tarski's definition shows that you have to take truth in a hierarchical

01:08:55.920 --> 01:09:08.800
way, and that there are more and more comprehensive truth predicates, but no limit, no most comprehensive

01:09:08.800 --> 01:09:12.520
short of contradiction.

01:09:12.520 --> 01:09:17.760
This is where I admire Tarski's result.

01:09:17.760 --> 01:09:23.560
Maybe I could say something about that.

01:09:23.560 --> 01:09:30.800
Tarski himself gives a number of extremely informal characterizations of the ordinary

01:09:30.800 --> 01:09:38.800
notion of truth, and among others he quotes Aristotle as you just did.

01:09:38.800 --> 01:09:47.120
I recently wrote a piece in which I said, I think Aristotle's characterization is better

01:09:47.480 --> 01:09:54.000
than Tarski's other informal characterizations for quite explicit reasons.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:58.480
Tarski's informal ones include ones which make it sound as though he thinks there's

01:09:58.480 --> 01:10:06.800
something that corresponds to a sentence that makes it true, the fact or something like

01:10:06.800 --> 01:10:11.920
that, and one of the merits of his actual constructions is that, of course, there are

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:21.200
no entities that correspond to sentences as a whole, except his infinite sequences, the

01:10:21.200 --> 01:10:31.360
satisfiers, so to speak, and they turn out not to be anything like facts, because if

01:10:31.360 --> 01:10:38.760
one sequence satisfies a closed sentence, so do they all, so there's no way of picking

01:10:38.760 --> 01:10:44.680
out the right facts, so to speak, in that way anyway, and Aristotle's characterization

01:10:44.680 --> 01:10:51.160
also doesn't talk about something that corresponds to a sentence, and it's more like Tarski's

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:56.320
actual work than Tarski's informal characterizations.

01:10:56.320 --> 01:11:02.640
But the informal characterization, of course, doesn't begin to do all the work for one thing.

01:11:02.640 --> 01:11:14.000
It only covers sentences of certain forms, curiously though, that is, you could say it

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:20.640
covers just those that start with an existential quantifier or the negation of an existential

01:11:20.640 --> 01:11:21.640
quantifier.

01:11:21.640 --> 01:11:28.480
Now, actually, the main example that Tarski gives is of languages that do all start that

01:11:28.520 --> 01:11:38.520
way, because he doesn't have any proper names and so forth.

01:11:38.520 --> 01:11:45.440
But of course, it tells us, I mean, the Aristotelian characterization tells us nothing about how

01:11:45.440 --> 01:11:51.680
truth is passed around, so to speak, in a language, even given the sentential connectives.

01:11:51.680 --> 01:11:53.600
Maybe negation would be the only one.

01:11:54.240 --> 01:11:58.320
It tells us a little bit about negation, but not much, but nothing about conjunction,

01:11:58.320 --> 01:12:00.320
alternation, and so forth.

01:12:00.320 --> 01:12:08.320
None of the work, so to speak, that a Tarski-type truth definition does in telling us how the

01:12:08.320 --> 01:12:14.720
truth, given finite information about a few cases, we can extend that now to an infinite

01:12:14.720 --> 01:12:20.560
number of cases, which tells us the kind of articulation that not only artificial languages

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:24.320
of the kind he was talking about have, but so do natural languages.

01:12:24.320 --> 01:12:30.320
They have all those devices, and he's given us a systematic way of thinking about them

01:12:30.320 --> 01:12:33.320
and coping with them.

01:12:33.320 --> 01:12:39.320
Yes, I took a different attitude towards that informal part of the Tarski thing.

01:12:39.320 --> 01:12:46.320
I took that as his generously administering to the vulgar mind before doing the kind of

